   31| """One of the oft-cited tenets of Python is that it is better to ask
   32| forgiveness than permission. That is, there are many cases where it is
   33| more inclusive and correct to handle exceptions than spend extra lines
   34| and execution time checking for conditions. This philosophy makes good
   35| exception handling features all the more important. Unfortunately
   36| Python's :mod:`traceback` module is woefully behind the times.
   37| 
   38| The ``tbutils`` module provides two disparate but complementary featuresets:
   39| 
   40|   1. With :class:`ExceptionInfo` and :class:`TracebackInfo`, the
   41|      ability to extract, construct, manipulate, format, and serialize
   42|      exceptions, tracebacks, and callstacks.
   43|   2. With :class:`ParsedException`, the ability to find and parse tracebacks
   44|      from captured output such as logs and stdout.
   45| 
   46| There is also the :class:`ContextualTracebackInfo` variant of
   47| :class:`TracebackInfo`, which includes much more information from each
   48| frame of the callstack, including values of locals and neighboring
   49| lines of code.
   50| """
   51| 
   52| 
   53| import re
   54| import sys
   55| import linecache
   56| 
